Loading Data

csv file was weird so had to:

  • read file manually
  • seperate by whitespace
  • convert to appropriate data types
  • assign header names to the columns
  • set the date as the index

filepath: /Users/neildevnani/Downloads/solar cycle:environment proj/kpdata.csv

In[44]:
import pandas as pd

# Define column names
column_names = [
    'year', 'month', 'day',
    'days_since_1932', 'days_midday',
    'bartels_rotation', 'bartels_day',
    'kp_00_03', 'kp_03_06', 'kp_06_09', 'kp_09_12',
    'kp_12_15', 'kp_15_18', 'kp_18_21', 'kp_21_24',
    'ap_00_03', 'ap_03_06', 'ap_06_09', 'ap_09_12',
    'ap_12_15', 'ap_15_18', 'ap_18_21', 'ap_21_24',
    'Ap', 'sunspot_number', 'f107_observed', 'f107_adjusted',
    'definitive_flag'
]


# Read file manually, clean quotes, and split by whitespace
with open("/Users/neildevnani/Downloads/solar cycle:environment proj/kpdata.csv", 'r') as f:
    data = [line.strip().replace('"', '').split() for line in f]

# Load into DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=column_names)

# Convert numeric columns to floats
for col in column_names:
    if col not in ['year', 'month', 'day']:
        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')

# Combine date columns
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df[['year', 'month', 'day']].astype(str).agg('-'.join, axis=1), format='%Y-%m-%d')

# Set date as index
df.set_index('date', inplace=True)

# Preview

Simplifying DF

  • dropping unecessary columns
  • replacing the 3hourly kp/ap columns to daily averages
  • only keeping definitive rows (dropping rows where definitive_flage = 1 or 0)
In[84]:
# Compute daily average of Kp only (Ap is already provided)
df['kp_mean'] = df[[f'kp_{hour}' for hour in ['00_03','03_06','06_09','09_12','12_15','15_18','18_21','21_24']]].mean(axis=1)

# Rename Ap to ap_mean for clarity
df['ap_mean'] = df['Ap']

# Keep minimal columns for modeling
df_ml = df[[
    'kp_mean', 'ap_mean', 'sunspot_number', 'f107_observed', 'definitive_flag'
]]

# Filter to only definitive data
df_ml = df_ml[df_ml['definitive_flag'] == 2]

Partition data (training data/testing data)

  • since data is time series, split data at a point and keep chronological
  • first 80% to train, last 20% to test
  • kp_mean is our target variable so set that to y.
  • All other variables are x but drop ap_mean since it is directly related to kp_mean.
In[171]:
# 80% train, 20% test based on date
split_date = df_ml.index[int(len(df_ml)*0.8)]

train = df_ml[df_ml.index < split_date]
test  = df_ml[df_ml.index >= split_date]

X_train = train[['ap_lag1', 'sunspot_lag1', 'f107_lag1']]
y_train = train['kp_mean']

X_test = test[['ap_lag1', 'sunspot_lag1', 'f107_lag1']]
y_test = test['kp_mean']

Add lagged kp

df_ml['kp_lag1'] = df_ml['kp_mean'].shift(1)
df_ml['kp_lag2'] = df_ml['kp_mean'].shift(2)
df_ml['kp_lag3'] = df_ml['kp_mean'].shift(3)

# Drop rows with missing lags
df_ml.dropna(inplace=True)

features = ['kp_lag1', 'kp_lag2', 'kp_lag3', 'ap_lag1', 'sunspot_lag1', 'f107_lag1']
target = 'kp_mean'

X = df_ml[features]
y = df_ml[target]

# Model
model = HistGradientBoostingRegressor()

# Metrics

Tuning the Histogram-based Gradient Boosting Regression Tree

Since finding that the RandomForest model is less accurate, we're going to focus on tuning the Histogram-based model.

In[205]:
from sklearn.ensemble import HistGradientBoostingRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer, r2_score
In[211]:
#Defining a parameter grid to search 
param_grid = {
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1],
    'max_iter': [100, 200, 300],
    'max_leaf_nodes': [15, 31, 63],
    'min_samples_leaf': [20, 50]
}

#Setup the model
hgb_model = HistGradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=42)

grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=hgb_model,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=3,  # 3-fold cross-validation
    scoring=make_scorer(r2_score),
    verbose=2,
    n_jobs=-1
)

#Run it
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

Fitting 3 folds for each of 54 candidates, totalling 162 fits
